english:
  title: Stele Inscription and Preface for National Teacher Gakjin, Posthumously Honored Venerable Gakryeom, Great Zen Master of the Jogye School
  author: Lee Dal-choong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the fourteenth year of Zhiyuan, the year of Yiwei, Venerable Gakryeom, Royal Teacher, passed into nirvana. Five years later, his disciples, including Wongyul, petitioned the king, saying: "Our master's deeds cannot be allowed to fade into obscurity. We humbly request that a stele be erected to preserve his memory." The king then commanded me to compose this inscription.

    Upon receiving this charge, I reflected thus: The ancients who achieved wisdom regarded the world as a mere inn and viewed rank and position as worn-out sandals. How much more so with those called Buddha's followers, who see all conditioned things as dreams and illusions, dwell in the unconditioned, and attain purity and extinction beyond all naming. Though we exhaust ourselves in praise, what benefit does this bring to the Master? Yet his disciples mourn him deeply because his teaching must have touched their hearts profoundly. Our king honors and trusts him because his way must have strengthened the realm. How could we not record this?

    In ancient times, our great founder established the kingdom. He left nothing undone that might support royal governance and protect the people's livelihood. Recognizing that the Buddha's teaching enriches our eastern land and harmonizes with both statecraft and education, he broadly established Buddhist temples to shelter the monks. Both Zen and doctrinal schools practiced according to their teachings to bless the realm, yet the Zen school flourished most greatly. Those who presided over its halls had to be worthy individuals—such was the reverence shown. Yet fearing that later generations might grow lax, the founder established ten articles of faith and proclaimed them. The first commanded: "Respect and have faith in the three treasures." From that time onward, only the most virtuous among the monks were elevated to serve as royal teachers in each generation. Generation after generation, the ceremonies became increasingly complete and refined.

    Our present sovereign, with keen attention and vigorous effort, labors day and night to govern well. All his actions follow the established ways; he consults with his ministers and visits the temples. He said: "As an unworthy youth who inherited the throne, I encounter difficult times and fear I lack the capacity to rule properly. I wish to honor among the monks one of supreme virtue to serve as my teacher, to assist in my governance, and to honor my ancestors' legacy. Who would be most fitting?" The ministers replied: "None equals Venerable Gakryeom. In the previous reign he was honored and given the title acknowledging his virtue." The king immediately commanded his officials to appoint him Royal Teacher. At that time the Master dwelt at Bulgap Temple. Given his advanced age and the difficult road, we dared not summon him in person. Instead, we had his portrait painted for veneration, and appointed Yi Jungji of Ikjae to write an eulogy. With great ceremony and propriety, we sent precious gifts to his dwelling to express our reverence as his students. The sincerity and respect shown were complete and profound. Upon receiving the king's letter, the Master said: "This old monk formerly received undeserved favor from the previous reign, unworthy occupying the position of royal teacher. Now I am again honored with this great command, which fills me with fear and shame. I can only earnestly tend the incense and humbly present blessings to His Majesty." This was in the second year of the present king's reign, the year Imjin.

    The Master's religious name was Bokgu, and he took the personal title Mueonsou, "the Silent Old Man." He was from Goseong county. His father was Yi Jonbee, who held the positions of Judge of the Secret Chancellery, Right Attendant, Scholar of Literature, and Keeper of the Privy Seal. The Master's family line was prominent both internally and externally, so I omit the genealogy here. He was a great Buddhist sage. His mother constantly recited the Great Vehicle sutras. Once she dreamed that a lay devotee, splendidly attired, appeared before her saying, "I have come." Soon after, she conceived and gave birth to him on the fifteenth day of the ninth month in the year Gyeongoh of Zhiyuan. His nature was luminous and pure, unlike ordinary children. As he grew, he naturally revered the Buddha's teaching; even his toys mimicked the order of temple halls. At merely ten years of age, he came to National Teacher Wonoh of the Jogye school, received the tonsure, and took the full precepts. Not long after, when National Teacher Wonoh entered nirvana, the Master followed the instructions left by his teacher and studied with Great Master Doyeong, pursuing the Way with tireless dedication. In ten years his learning was perfected, and the assembly recognized him as their foremost guide. In autumn of the year Gyeongiin, he achieved the highest rank in the Zen examination at the age of twenty-one. His vision had already transcended the ordinary; devoted solely to the Way, he spurned worldly entanglement. He wandered like clouds seeking the path, sat motionless as a clod observing mind, lingered leisurely by streams and rocks, drifted freely through forests and clouds, and vowed never to tread the path of fame.

    National Teacher Jigak was his second teacher, who treated him with utmost respect. When Jigak entrusted his disciples to the Master, he replied: "Only after gaining understanding within oneself can one transmit it to others. I do not presume to undertake this responsibility." He then went to Baekam Temple and, together with several fellow seekers, pursued intensive practice for more than ten years. His residence at Songwang Temple of Wol-Nam lasted forty-plus years. During this time, his works benefiting the nation and people, as well as the honors and gifts he received, are too numerous to recount—yet these too were but the dregs of his legacy, so I do not record them.

    In his final years, he dwelt at Bulgap Temple at the king's command. He told his disciples: "Once I slept on this mountain and dreamed a figure came before me, bowed, and said, 'Master, you should dwell here.' At the time I wondered at this dream alone, but now it is verified." He composed this verse:

    The king bestowed Bulgap's mountain peak,
    Yet men say the weary bird knows how to return.
    With reverent devotion I pray for heaven's span of years,
    That from this time the realm's foundation endures for ten thousand ages.

    Thus his earnest concern for king and country is evident.

    In the year Yiwei, he moved to Baekam Temple. In the sixth month he fell ill. On the twenty-seventh day of the seventh month, his illness eased. He sealed a letter of farewell to the king and court, requesting the magistrate to affix the official seal. After changing his robes, cutting his hair, bathing, and donning his ceremonial vestments, he commanded his attendants to beat the drum. Sitting on a meditation seat, he spoke this final verse:

    The mind itself is Buddha—the old man of Jiangxi;
    Not Buddha, not mind—the sage beyond the world.
    In the flying squirrel's cry I depart alone,
    Nirvana and rebirth have always been empty.

    With serene composure, he entered nirvana. Purple clouds filled the valley, and his face glowed like powder and rouge. The next day his disciples wept as they performed the cremation at the western peak below the temple. His remains were placed in an urn and brought back to Bulgap Temple. In the twelfth month, the king sent an envoy to pay condolences and bestowed the posthumous title National Teacher Gakjin. His stupa was named Ciyun. He lived eighty-six springs and seventy-six summers of monastic life.

    He was by nature quiet, pure, and unaffected—dignified, peaceful, upright, and sincere. His brow was blue-topped, his eyebrows streaked with white, his lips red, his teeth white. From a distance he appeared crystalline as an immortal; draw near and he seemed warm as a parent. His mouth spoke no judgment of others; his heart harbored only reverence. Throughout his life as abbot, he kept not a single possession. His dharma lineage descended from National Teacher Pocho through thirteen generations to himself. Among his outstanding disciples were Seonwon, Baekwha, Gaji, and Magok, with more than a thousand followers in all. His nephew Haengchon, now a renowned minister, is our model. Haengchon's younger brother, Director of Personnel, was my contemporary friend, and I later participated with him in the privy council. Subsequently I received several letters from him, which I treasure greatly. Therefore, though my literary skill is humble and poor, I have ventured to compose this inscription.

    The inscription reads:

    High yet without danger—
    This is how our Master moved.
    Low in self-cultivation—
    This is our King's blessing.

    The great path divides into many ways,
    Yet all root in the one source.
    Mutual support brings salvation,
    Auspice blooms throughout the world.

    For thousands upon ten thousand years,
    Let radiance shine before and after.
    Engraved upon stone, these words
    Are but dregs and chaff,
    Yet we hope that through long ages past and future,
    They will not be forgotten.
